author: MrOaiki
body: I have no idea what news has recently come out to warrant the company’s depreciation. But I do believe Cloudflare’s biggest competitor is Amazon. Cloudflare are huge when it comes to CDNs, but Amazon has their own delivery networks and they’re building new data centers all over the world. You can of course run your server on Amazon’s web services and use Cloudflare’s CDN, but companies that move to AWS tend to go for an all AWS solution eventually.

author: Meymo
body:
Even if the market crashes or goes sideways, as long as you keep buying in on a regular cadence, you will succeed. 

People often like to think, “well what if the market is sideways for a decade?!?” Okay, if that happens and you keep buying in every 2-weeks or every month, when the market goes up you’ll also have a bunch more money invested which will increase in value as well. 

If you’re under 55, there’s no reason to ever consider exiting 100%. Would you really stop your 401k, HSA, or IRA just because of a couple of bad years? 

Invesco did a great infographic which describes the bull and bear markets over time. Since 1957, The average bear market only lasts 1 year.


https://www.invesco.com/us-rest/contentdetail?contentId=049233173f5c3510VgnVCM100000c2f1bf0aRCRD&audienceType=investors

We’ve been in a bear market for around 90 days now. If this is an average bear market, then the odds are we will start the next bull market either this year or early next year. Again, this assumes the historical trends hold.

With the amount of money and policy changes that are being pumped into the system, it wouldn’t surprise me to see this current bear market end much sooner than one year from now. 

Time will tell. Good luck!

author: bbbpppccc
body:
Having worked for years in startups and enterprises, I’ve seen the move away from third party cdns to cloud specific cdns. Especially for companies moving from on prem to the cloud.

They offer less hops into the network, tighter security, ddos mitigation, and well its easier for accounting (this matters mostly for enterprises).

The only times I’ve ever recommended cloud flare before, were for smaller businesses with like zero technical understanding.

I’m personally never going to touch cloudflare/fastly

author: orebright
body: As someone who's worked remotely for many years now in a fully remote team, I think at least some segment of workers will want to do this permanently. This might cause some shift though it may not be drastic. A lot of factors go into this. The biggest one I tend to see is people don't set up their space to be a hybrid work/live place. They just do work where they usually entertain (living room/couch, on their laptop) and this leads to much faster burnout because you can easily work too much, or get easily distracted and struggle with focus because you're giving your mind mixed signals. It's been very important to me to have an office space, whether that's a dedicated desk in a living room or a completely dedicated office in the house. With the right setup I think working from home is fantastic and most people would probably enjoy it, but with the wrong setup most are going to get very tired of it and want to go back to an office asap. So in my opinion we won't see a "plummet" but there will likely be some noticeable effect from workers who got in the right cadence and prefer working at home.

author: Albedo100
body:
This is not uncommon. Dropbox has a 75% gross profit margin and has the same marketcap with over 5x the revenue. Even salesforce has that margin and is barely positive. 

I'm not convinced a company like Cloudflare and Fastly can just drop their sales and be profitable. Switching between CDNs is one of the easiest things a tech department can do. It's literally drag and drop stuff or a couple lines of code. It's not like using salesforce where it benefits from being an expert in it and you have an entire team developed around using it. 

CDN stocks are just a flavor of the season and are pumping high because of their low market caps.

author: pharmacykiller33
body:
You’ll get there if you go to medical school, but it takes time developing a cadence. I completed 2 years of residency as well and was fortunate in the match process to get into a great program. 

For starters, look at your inclusion criteria and see what “clinical question” they are answering. Does the therapy fill a void or is it replacing standard of care? If it’s going for new SOC was their trial design set up to evaluate it compared to current standard of care or was it compared to a weak comparator to help it get approved. That’s the problem with the approval process now. Weak agents are getting compared to crappy regimens to make it look better. 

Follow major physicians on twitter. You’ll learn exponentially faster in how they think about things.
